\begin_layout Subsection
Regulation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fixed income markets are subject to commercial, customer protection, contract
 and corporate laws.
 In 2010 the following key points were adpoted: improving the transparency;
 stability oversight council; tighting securitization rules; capital requirement
s.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There rules govern how a bond (or other security) can be traded.
 Limitations are imposed on HFT (in order to safeguard).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MiFID II: improve corporate governancse; stronger investor protection; extend
 transaction reporting and transparency.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are several regulators, most of them can be found in any country:
 Banking supersvision (U.S: the Federal Reserve Bank), Insurance & Financial
 Services supervision, Capital market supervision, Anti-trust supervision.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fixed Income Market
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The U.S issues zero-coupon T-bills at discount (YTM), semiannual coupon bearing
 T-notes, T-bonds, TIPS.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All treasuries are issued through a public bid and are traded through brokers
 on the secondary market.
 They are vulnerable to reinvestment, interest and (except TIPS) inflation
 risk.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The federal agency securities securities are federally-related institutions
 (implicit) or government-sponsored enterprises (explicit).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Municipal FI securities (towns / states) are generally less trusted than
 the government (they cannot print money).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Corporate FI securities consist of corporate bonds (secured / credit-enhanced),
 notes and commercial papers.
\end_layout

